# No workarounds — fix root causes

## Policy

Do **not** add workarounds that hide broken behavior. Fix why it fails (API, auth, CORS, schema, env, native shell). Workarounds fail the next session, platform, or deploy.

**Workaround (reject):**
- Local flags/cache that contradict server state **only** because PATCH/POST failed
- Renaming or “repairing” bad API rows in the UI instead of fixing create/update + validation
- Skipping errors (empty catch, swallow 401, reload to “reset” state)
- Wrong third-party URLs or aliases instead of the correct contract
- “Works on device if you delete data / avoid path X”

**Real fix (do this):**
- Correct auth for the platform (e.g. Capacitor Bearer when cookies cannot cross-origin)
- Server persists what the client depends on (`onboarding_completed`, app `name`/`slug`, etc.)
- CORS / env / OAuth config documented and set in deployment
- API returns complete, validated payloads; client validates and surfaces failures clearly
- Defensive parsing at boundaries (null-safe) **without** pretending sync succeeded

## When proposing a change

1. State **root cause** in one sentence.
2. State **fix** (what file/service/config changes).
3. If something still fails, **toast/error + failed request** — not silent local override.

## Allowed patterns (not workarounds)

- Platform-correct transport (Bearer in WebView, cookies on same-site web)
- Offline cache **only** as an explicit product feature with defined merge rules and server reconciliation
- Legitimate fallbacks (brand not on icon CDN → letter tile) **after** correct slug lookup fails

## If a true fix needs infra you cannot do in-repo

Say so plainly. Do not ship a client mask instead. List what the user must set (Railway env, rebuild native, etc.).
